<section>
  <title>Properties of Conjugation</title>
  <proposition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be
        <m>n \times n</m> matrices with <m>B</m> invertible.
        Conjugation preserves determinants:
        <m>\det A = \det B^{-1}AB</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </proposition>
  <proposition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be invertible
        <m>n \times n</m> matrices in a finite matrix group <m>G</m>.
        Then the order of <m>A</m> is the same as the order of <m>B^{-1}AB</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </proposition>
  <proposition>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be
        <m>n \times n</m> matrices with <m>B</m> invertible.
        The number of fixed points of <m>A</m> is the same as the number of fixed points of <m>B^{-1}AB</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </proposition>
</section>